member.remarks:
Goto state pops the current and pushes the specified on the active state stack. This is shorthand for the following code:
class Event E { } [OnEventGotoState(typeof(E), typeof(S))] this.RaiseEvent(new E());
This event is not handled until the action that calls this method returns control back to the Coyote runtime. It is handled before any other events are dequeued from the inbox. Only one of the following can be called per action: , , or and . An Assert is raised if you accidentally try and do two of these operations in a single action.

Goto state pops the current and pushes the specified on the active state stack. This is shorthand for the following code:
class Event E { } [OnEventGotoState(typeof(E), typeof(S))] this.RaiseEvent(new E());
This event is not handled until the action that calls this method returns control back to the Coyote runtime. It is handled before any other events are dequeued from the inbox. Only one of the following can be called per action: , , or and . An Assert is raised if you accidentally try and do two of these operations in a single action.

Pushing a state does not pop the current , instead it pushes the specified on the active state stack so that you can have multiple active states. In this case events can be handled by all active states on the stack. This is shorthand for the following code:
class Event E { } [OnEventPushState(typeof(E), typeof(S))] this.RaiseEvent(new E());
This event is not handled until the action that calls this method returns control back to the Coyote runtime. It is handled before any other events are dequeued from the inbox. Only one of the following can be called per action: , , or and . An Assert is raised if you accidentally try and do two of these operations in a single action.

